
	
<p>
Project Euler 15 analyses taxicab geometry. This system replaces the usual distance function with the sum of the absolute differences of their Cartesian coordinates. In other words, the distance a taxi would travel in a grid plan instead of the shortest distance between two points. In chess, the distance between squares on the chessboard for rooks is measured in taxicab distance.</p>
<p>
The fifteenth Euler problem asks to determine the number of possible routes a taxi can take in a city. This problem is logically similar to <a href="https://lucidmanager.org/data-science/project-euler-18/">Euler Problem 18 and 67</a>.</p>
<figure>
<div style="position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
